         <br>
      Whoa!!!  <br />
Hmmm, if someone asks another person, "what was the outcome of (fill in the blank team, game, players, etc.,) a specific sporting event, one could answer, "Tommy Haas was the winner, and Marat Safin was the loser."  Grant it, it is not the best grammar but, people do speak that way.  Now, when a tennis match, "tennis lover," is completed, and you make a derogatory comment about an opponent, bt calling them a "loser,"  that is just plain unsportsmanship-like, extremely judgemental, and does show some "weird" kind of bias of which you just accused some of the fellow forum members here, of.<br />
<br />
Duh, yes this is the MS Official Site, and I would certainly hope that all of his fans would not be here, just so that they can "slam" (no tennis pun intended,) Safin everytime he should have a misstep.  I don't get to this forum but, from what I see...from the webmaster, and all the way through...these fans stick to their guns, and they DO seem to know their tennis, "tennis lover?!?!?"<br />
<br />
I for one started the season a tad frustrated with the outcome of his play but, only an idiot would not have to take into consideration, that athletes such as a tennis players (there really aren't many athletes out there...think of American baseball players, etc.) where you have to be in top phycical form, have the skills and knowledge, the drive and the endurance, have to put in a lot of work to get back after such a lay-off. to rebuild the mental & physical aspects that previously had him playing so well.  Yes, I would scrutinize his games, and say out loud, "come on...move,move..." because he appeared to be "sluggish" in the motivational sense, which of course effects the physical, mental, blah, blah, blah.  Give the man a break...he went through a lot of emotional stuff (that was most likely more painful than the knee,) and wow, if you have been keeping an objective eye on him....look how he has "progressed" for the better in the latter half/end of season.  Have you seen any recent matches?  He is fighting his way back...and yeah, he is going to lose a match or two, or five but, it is so glaringly obvious that he is back on track.  <br />
<br />
You don't need to be a Safin fan to see it - you don''t have to be a player to see it - you don't even have to be a tennis fan to see it...it is night & day.  Try and be more open-minded, give the guy not only a break but, acknowledge the strides he has made (when at one point it may have looked like he was giving up or "finished,") and most of all, listen to his newfound "old" determination to go out there and play the best tennis he can.  And on the "open-minded" topic...get rid of that small-minded attitude you just spewed at the fans here!!!<br />
<br />
Sorry for the length all...just a tad thrown by such harsh words...I'll keep future post smaller.<br />
<br />
Way to go Safin...look how far ye have come this season!!!    Woo-hoo!!!!  God, I sound like a tennis lover...I am, and I suspect that is why I am a Safin fan...he's shown us this year that he may have been down...but he was not gonna stay there for long!!</font></tt><p>
    </td>
  </tr>
